---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "What is Portfolio Rebalancing? A Guide to Risk Management",
    "description": "Learn the mechanics of portfolio rebalancing, when and how to adjust your asset allocation, use rebalancing bands, and handle tax implications.",
    "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/what-is-rebalancing"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does it mean to rebalance a portfolio?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Rebalancing is the process of realigning the weightings of a portfolio of assets. It involves buying or selling assets to maintain an original or desired level of asset allocation and risk."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How often should I rebalance my portfolio?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Investors typically rebalance on a calendar basis (e.g., annually or semi-annually) or based on tolerance bands (e.g., whenever an asset drifts 5% or 10% from its target allocation)."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does rebalancing trigger taxes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "If done in a taxable account, selling assets to rebalance will trigger capital gains taxes. However, rebalancing within tax-advantaged accounts like an RRSP or TFSA does not trigger immediate tax consequences."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="What is Portfolio Rebalancing? Risk Management Guide"
  description="Master portfolio rebalancing. Understand asset allocation drift, learn how to use tolerance bands, and discover the tax implications of realigning your investments."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/what-is-rebalancing"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is Portfolio Rebalancing?</h1>
      <p>Mastering Asset Allocation, Tolerance Bands, and Tax Implications.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="intro-section">
      <p>Portfolio rebalancing is the process of realigning the weightings of a portfolio of assets. It involves periodically buying or selling assets in your portfolio to maintain your original, desired level of asset allocation or risk. Over time, as investments generate varying returns, your portfolio will naturally "drift" away from your target strategy.</p>
      <p>As you expand your knowledge beyond the basics found in our <a href="/investing-glossary">Investing Glossary</a>, rebalancing becomes the primary tool for managing risk. Whether you hold individual stocks or broad <a href="/what-is-etf">Exchange Traded Funds (ETFs)</a>, disciplined rebalancing is what separates professional portfolio management from emotional, haphazard investing.</p>
    </section>

    <h2>Why Do Portfolios Drift?</h2>
    <p>Imagine you start with a simple asset allocation: 60% Stocks and 40% Bonds. You have $100,000 invested.</p>
    <div class="card">
      <p><strong>The Drift Scenario:</strong> Let's say it's a massive bull market for stocks. Over the next three years, your stock holdings double in value, while your bond holdings remain flat.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Initial Portfolio:</strong> $60,000 Stocks (60%) / $40,000 Bonds (40%). Total: $100,000.</li>
        <li><strong>Current Portfolio:</strong> $120,000 Stocks / $40,000 Bonds. Total: $160,000.</li>
        <li><strong>New Allocation:</strong> Your portfolio is now 75% Stocks ($120k / $160k) and 25% Bonds ($40k / $160k).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>While you've made excellent returns, your portfolio has drastically shifted from a balanced risk profile (60/40) to an aggressive one (75/25). If the stock market suddenly crashes by 40%, your portfolio will suffer far more damage than you originally planned for when you set your 60/40 target.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How to Rebalance Your Portfolio</h2>
    <p>To bring your portfolio back to its 60/40 target, you must <strong>rebalance</strong>. There are two primary ways to achieve this:</p>

    <h3>1. Selling High and Buying Low (The Standard Method)</h3>
    <p>The most common method is to sell a portion of the asset class that has outperformed and use the proceeds to buy the asset class that has underperformed.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>In our example above, you need your $160,000 portfolio to be 60% Stocks ($96,000) and 40% Bonds ($64,000).</li>
      <li>You would sell $24,000 of your stock ETFs and buy $24,000 of your bond ETFs.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This action forces you to follow the golden rule of investing: <strong>Buy low, sell high.</strong> By rebalancing mechanically, you strip the emotion out of the process, preventing yourself from getting too greedy at market peaks or too fearful at market bottoms.</p>

    <h3>2. Rebalancing Through New Contributions</h3>
    <p>If you are still in the accumulation phase of your life, the most tax-efficient way to rebalance is by directing new money to the underweighted asset class.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Instead of selling your outperforming stocks, you simply direct all your new <a href="/what-is-dollar-cost-averaging">Dollar Cost Averaging (DCA)</a> contributions toward buying bonds until the 60/40 balance is restored.</li>
      <li>This method avoids triggering capital gains taxes and transaction fees, though it may take several months to achieve your target allocation depending on the size of your portfolio and contributions.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>When Should You Rebalance?</h2>
    <p>There are two widely accepted strategies for determining when it's time to rebalance:</p>

    <h3>Calendar Rebalancing</h3>
    <p>This involves picking a specific date (e.g., January 1st, or your birthday) and rebalancing on that day every year, or perhaps semi-annually. The advantage of calendar rebalancing is its sheer simplicity. It takes very little time and enforces strict discipline. The disadvantage is that in a highly volatile year, your portfolio could drift significantly off-target between your scheduled dates.</p>

    <h3>Tolerance Band Rebalancing</h3>
    <p>A more sophisticated approach is to set "tolerance bands" (or corridors) for each asset class. Instead of a date, you rebalance only when an asset class drifts a certain percentage away from its target weight.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Example:</strong> You set a 5% tolerance band on your 60% stock allocation. You will do nothing as long as stocks represent between 55% and 65% of your portfolio.</li>
      <li>If stocks surge to 66%, the band is breached, and you immediately execute trades to bring them back down to 60%.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This method often yields better results in volatile markets but requires you to monitor your portfolio more frequently. It works particularly well when managing allocations between Large, Mid, and Small-cap stocks (see <a href="/what-is-market-cap">What is Market Cap</a>) because different sizes of companies will often drift out of alignment during economic cycles.</p>

    <h2>Tax Implications of Rebalancing</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <p>Rebalancing in a standard taxable brokerage account means you are actively selling profitable investments, which will trigger capital gains taxes. Depending on your tax bracket and how long you held the asset, this tax drag can severely reduce your long-term compound returns.</p>
      <p>This is why tax-advantaged accounts are so vital for portfolio management. In Canada, rebalancing within an <a href="/what-is-rrsp">RRSP</a> or a <a href="/what-is-tfsa">TFSA</a> triggers no capital gains taxes. You can sell your high-flying stocks and buy bonds inside the account completely tax-free.</p>
      <p>Advanced investors use a strategy called "Asset Location." They might keep their high-growth, high-turnover investments inside tax-sheltered accounts where they can be rebalanced freely, while keeping investments that generate favorable <a href="/what-is-dividend-yield">Dividend Yields</a> in taxable accounts, depending on local tax laws regarding eligible dividends.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Rebalancing and the P/E Ratio</h2>
    <p>Sometimes investors rebalance not just across asset classes (Stocks vs. Bonds), but within the equity portion of their portfolio. For instance, if you noticed the <a href="/what-is-pe-ratio">P/E Ratio</a> of your technology sector ETF has skyrocketed to 60 (indicating extreme overvaluation), while your financial sector ETF is sitting at a P/E of 10, you might choose to rebalance by trimming the tech ETF and buying the financial ETF, locking in gains before a potential tech correction.</p>
    <p>Rebalancing is the ultimate defense against letting a portfolio run wild. It forces discipline, manages risk, and ensures your investments continually reflect your long-term goals rather than short-term market noise.</p>

    <div class="card FAQ">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What does it mean to rebalance a portfolio?</summary>
        <p>Rebalancing is the process of realigning the weightings of a portfolio of assets. It involves buying or selling assets to maintain an original or desired level of asset allocation and risk.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How often should I rebalance my portfolio?</summary>
        <p>Investors typically rebalance on a calendar basis (e.g., annually or semi-annually) or based on tolerance bands (e.g., whenever an asset drifts 5% or 10% from its target allocation).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Does rebalancing trigger taxes?</summary>
        <p>If done in a taxable account, selling assets to rebalance will trigger capital gains taxes. However, rebalancing within tax-advantaged accounts like an RRSP or TFSA does not trigger immediate tax consequences.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

